===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|mous|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|mūs}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*mūs}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*muh₂s}}.
{{rel-top|cognates}}
Germanic cognates include Old Frisian {{term|mūs|lang=ofs}}, Old Saxon {{m|osx|mūs}} (Dutch {{term|muis|lang=nl}}), Old High German {{m|goh|mūs}} (German {{term|Maus|lang=de}}), Old Norse {{term|mús|lang=non}} (Swedish {{term|mus|lang=sv}}, Danish {{term|mus|lang=da}}, Norwegian {{term|mus|lang=nl}}, Icelandic {{term|mús|lang=is}}, Faroese {{term|mús|lang=fo}}).

Indo-European cognates include Ancient Greek {{term|μῦς|lang=grc}}, Latin {{m|la|mūs}}, Armenian {{term|մուկ|lang=hy|sc=Armn|tr=muk}}, Old Church Slavonic {{term|мꙑшь|sc=Cyrs|lang=cu}} (Russian {{term|sc=Cyrl|мышь|lang=ru}}), Albanian {{term|mi|mī|lang=sq}}, Persian {{term|sc=fa-Arab|موش|tr=muš|lang=fa}}, Sanskrit {{term|sc=Deva|मूष्|tr=mūṣ|lang=sa}}
